                            <comment id="65459" author="gonzalad" created="Tue, 19 Apr 2011 02:12:27 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Hello,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I want just to better understand this issue SimpleJdbcTemplate is being deprecated.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So :&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;when using named parameters in my sql, I should use NamedParameterJdbcTemplate ? Or will it be deprecated to ?&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;when I don&apos;t need named parameters, yoyu confirm I should just use JdbcTemplate ?&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;


&lt;p&gt;Thanks for the info !&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="65469" author="thomas.risberg" created="Tue, 19 Apr 2011 05:06:32 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Hi Adrian,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Yes to both. NamedParameterJdbcTemplate is remaining and should be used for named parameter use. If you don&apos;t want to create two templates you can always call getJdbcOperations() on the NamedParameterJdbcTemplate to get access to the regular JdbcOperations interface of the JdbcTemplate.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The SimpleJdbcTemplate was initially added to provide some Java 5 syntax sugar and we later added the named parameter support. There really is no need for three different template implementations any longer.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So, use the JdbcTemplate unless you need the named parameter support in which case you should use the NamedParameterJdbcTemplate.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;-Thomas&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="65475" author="gonzalad" created="Tue, 19 Apr 2011 13:46:55 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Thanks very much Thomas for the explanation&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="68512" author="desmethans" created="Mon, 18 Jul 2011 08:39:38 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Does this mean SimpleJdbcInsert will also be deprecated ?  I don&apos;t know of methods as convenient as the simpleJdbcInsert methods in JdbcTemplate.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="68515" author="thomas.risberg" created="Mon, 18 Jul 2011 09:36:29 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;No, SimpleJdbcInsert and SimpleJdbcCall will remain. Like you said there is no other implementation that provides these features. SimpleJdbcTemplate  was the odd man out since its feature set was mostly replicated in JdbcTemplate and NamedParameterJdbcTemplate.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;-Thomas&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="75740" author="srini.s" created="Sun, 12 Feb 2012 21:45:16 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;org.springframework.test.context.junit4.AbstractTransactionalJUnit4SpringContextTests still uses SimpleJdbcTemplate. May I know when this class will be updated to using JdbcTemplate?&lt;br/&gt;
Spring version : 3.1.0 M2&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="75845" author="cbeams" created="Wed, 15 Feb 2012 12:15:46 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;@Srinivasan - feel free to open a new issue about this, but no further action will be taken on this particular issue.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
